<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#2f2f4f">Originally posted by Halthek Naugrim on 03-26-2001 03:10 PM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">Not so much a game, but it was definitely Dwarven fun.

I was sitting with some friends in Emerald Jungle (ogre warrior, enchanter, and another cleric).  I was dry, but luckily the other cleric had some ale on him and passed it out.  The ogre gets himself hammered and went out to pull.  It was great fun watching him run into trees on his way out.  Because he couldn't see straight he brought back 4 friends instead of the usual one or two.  The enchanter proceeded to mez the extras while the ogre proceeded to break mez as on just about everything.  The ogre's health started to fall fast...  Here is where it gets fun.  I wasn't about to be out drunk by an ogre, so I down half a stack of ale and try to cast complete heal.  Of course I can't (next time remember: root first then drink).  The other cleric stays sober and tries to heal but it is too late; we have a dead ogre on our hands.  The other cleric and enchanter take off for the zone with all but one gorilla which remained mezzed.  I walked down to the gorilla and slapped it up side the head (I was empty handed).  I continued to try and punch while it had no problem at all making quick work of me.  Another ogre even stopped by to watch and offered to help me.  :)  Anyway, I received a free trip to North Freeport where I bought more ale for everyone!  I haven't had so much fun in-game in a long time.

Now for the serious question...  I played around with the root self, drink, heal routine for a while after this.  Half the time I resisted my own roots.  When I could get root to stick it was usually only for a couple of seconds.  Only once did it last long enough for a complete heal to finish casting.  How can I make this work better?  Should I use something other than root?  Any suggestions would be greatly appreciated.  :)


------------------
Halthek Naugrim - Cleric - 51
Master Brewer
Mithaniel Marr</TEXTAREA>
